net.njcull.collections

Class ImmutableUniSortedArrayMap<K,V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
      • net.njcull.collections.ImmutableUniSortedArrayMap<K,V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - the type of keys maintained by this map
    V - the type of mapped values
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.util.Map<K,V>, java.util.SortedMap<K,V>, ArrayBackedMap<K,V>

    public final class ImmutableUniSortedArrayMap<K,V>
extends java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
implements ArrayBackedMap<K,V>, java.util.SortedMap<K,V>, java.io.Serializable
    A SortedMap backed by an array of elements. The array is the exact length required to contain the keys and values. Only keys are sorted.

    Keys and values are stored together in sorted key order.

    Keys are tested using a binary search implementation. The map's keyset and entryset views may also be viewed as a List.

    Version:
    7/01/2016.

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Returns a string representation of this map. The string representation consists of a list of key-value mappings in the order returned by the map's entryAt indexer, enclosed in braces ("{}"). Adjacent mappings are separated by the characters ", " (comma and space). Each key-value mapping is rendered as the key followed by an equals sign ("=") followed by the associated value. Keys and values are converted to strings as by String.valueOf(Object).

        This implementation is handled as a static method rather than a default method because a default method cannot override any methods of Object.

        Overrides:
        toString in class java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
        Returns:
        a string representation of this map

      • hashCode

        public int hashCode()
        Returns the hash code value for this map. The hash code of a map is defined to be the sum of the hash codes of each entry in the map's entrySet() view. This ensures that m1.equals(m2) implies that m1.hashCode()==m2.hashCode() for any two maps m1 and m2, as required by the general contract of Object.hashCode().

        This implementation is handled as a static method rather than a default method because a default method cannot override any methods of Object.

        Specified by:
        hashCode in interface java.util.Map<K,V>
        Overrides:
        hashCode in class java.util.AbstractMap<K,V>
        Returns:
        the hash code value for this map
